{% import "product-components.njk" as pc %}
<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Compliance</strong> standardizes the <strong>enforcement</strong> layer &mdash; deliberately
    separated from <em>conformance</em>. The distinction is the whole point:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.95rem;">
    <li><strong>Conformance</strong> = <em>how aligned</em> something is to a standard &mdash; a
      <strong>measure</strong> on a spectrum (the <code>check:app-conformance</code> benchmark, conformance
      demos, <code>conformanceLevel</code>). It <em>reports</em>; it doesn't block.</li>
    <li><strong>Compliance</strong> = a conformance criterion <strong>promoted to an enforced hard
      rule</strong> &mdash; a gate, with severity, pass/fail, expiring waivers, and an audit trail. A team
      <em>chooses</em> to move a measure into a hard rule; from then on it is reported as compliance.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Web Compliance owns that promotion path and the machinery around it. The benchmark's
    <code>--strict</code> flag is the seed; this project generalizes it into a declared, severity-aware
    policy. The canonical artifact is the <strong>policy/rule model</strong> &mdash; policy-as-code,
    versioned, that <strong>extends a fully-defined platform-default policy</strong> (a baseline of gates
    every project inherits, then extends or overrides), consistent with every other Web Everything config
    layer.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">Not Web Policy, not a report protocol of its own</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <a href="/projects/webpolicy/">Web Policy</a> owns declarative <em>domain</em> rules &mdash; whether a
      business <em>action</em> is permitted ("orders over $X need sign-off"). Web Compliance gates
      <em>standards conformance</em> ("aria-sort must reach L2 before merge") &mdash; a different subject
      with its own home. And it needs <strong>no compliance-specific protocol</strong>: compliance's
      <em>results</em> (audit / gate outcomes) ride <a href="/projects/webreporting/">Web Reporting</a>'s
      report model &mdash; an audit result is just another report source. A separate policy-interchange
      protocol is added only if a concrete cross-vendor need appears.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

